# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The **American Library Association** (**ALA**) is a nonprofit organization based in the United States that promotes libraries and library education internationally.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] It is the oldest and largest library association in the world.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] During the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, 103 librarians (90 men and 13 women) responded to a call for a "Convention of Librarians" to be held October 4–6, 1876, at the Historical Society of Pennsylvania.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In his seminal essay "ALA at 100", Edward G.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Holley describes how "the register was passed around for all to sign who wished to become charter members" at the end of the meeting, which is why the date of the founding of the ALA is considered to be October 6, 1876 (1876-10-06).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Attendees came from as far west as Chicago and from England.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1879, the ALA was chartered in Massachusetts.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA's headquarters office is in Chicago.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Another important founder was Frederick Leypoldt, publisher of Library Journal, who published the conference proceedings.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] From 1876 until 1885, Justin Winsor served as the first president of the ALA.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Many early presidents were also officers in the Bibliographical Society of America.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] During World War I the ALA Executive Board initiated by Walter Lewis Brown established the Library War Service Committee to supply books and periodicals to military personnel at home and overseas.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The American Library in Paris was founded as part of this effort.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In the 1930s, library activists pressured the American Library Association to be more responsive to issues such as peace, segregation, library unions, and intellectual freedom.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1931, the Junior Members Round Table (JMRT) was formed to provide a voice for the younger members of the ALA.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The first Library Bill of Rights (LBR) was drafted by Forrest Spaulding to set a standard against censorship and was adopted by the ALA in 1939.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] This has been recognized as the moment defining modern librarianship as a profession committed to intellectual freedom and the right to read.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] ALA appointed a committee to study censorship and recommend policy after the banning of the novel *The Grapes of Wrath* in Kern County, California and the implementation of the Library Bill of Rights.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The committee reported in 1940 that intellectual freedom and professionalism were linked and recommended a permanent committee – Committee on Intellectual Freedom.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA made revisions to strengthen the Library Bill of Rights in June 1948, approved the Statement on Labeling in 1951 to discourage labeling material as subversive, and adopted the Freedom to Read Statement and the Overseas Library Statement in 1953.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA has worked throughout its history to define, extend, protect and advocate for equity of access to information.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1945, the ALA established an Office in Washington, D.C. named the National Relations Office under the direction of Paul Howard.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1961, the ALA took a stand regarding service to African Americans and others, advocating for equal library service for all.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] An amendment to the Library Bill of Rights was passed in 1961 that made clear that an individual's library use should not be denied or abridged because of race, religion, national origin, or political views.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Some communities decided to close their doors rather than desegregate.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1963, the ALA commissioned a study, *Access to Public Libraries*, which found direct and indirect discrimination in American libraries.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1967, some librarians protested against a pro-Vietnam War speech given by General Maxwell D.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] This group called themselves the Organizing Committee for the ALA Round Table on Social Responsibilities of Libraries.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] This group drew in many other under-represented groups in the ALA who lacked power, including the Congress for Change in 1969.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] This formation of the committee was approved in 1969 and would change its name to the Social Responsibilities Round Table (SRRT) in 1971.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] After its inception, the Round Table of Social Responsibilities began to press ALA leadership to address issues such as library unions, working conditions, wages, and intellectual freedom.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Freedom to Read Foundation was founded by Judith Krug, Alexander Allain, and Carrie C Robinson and established by ALA's executive board in 1969.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The American Library Association celebrated its centennial in 1976.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The American Library Association Archives, established at the time of the centennial, created an online exhibit which includes a history of the centennial.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1979 and 1991 the ALA collaborated with the National Commission on Libraries and Information Science on two White House Conferences.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In June 1990, the ALA approved "Policy on Library Services to the Poor" and in 1996 the Task Force on Hunger, Homelessness, and Poverty was formed to resurrect and promote the ALA guidelines on library services to the poor.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Office for Information Technology Policy was established in 1995 to act as a public policy advocate for libraries in the area of information technology.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The "Congress on Professional Education" took place from April 30 to May 1, 1999, in Washington, D.C.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Its purpose was to reach consensus among stakeholder groups on the values and core competencies of the profession and on strategies for action to address common issues and concerns.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] At the beginning of the century The Congress on Professional Education recommended that the Association develop a set of Core Values.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2018, the ALA Council unanimously adopted a resolution acknowledging ALA's accountability for not participating in the fight against library segregation during the era of Jim Crow laws and honoring African American librarians who did fight, including Clara Stanton Jones, E.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The day it was signed, ALA President Jim Neal read the resolution at an event where Joan Mattison Daniel of the Greenville Eight, Ethel Adolphe, Ibrahim Mumin, and Teri Moncure Mojgani shared their experiences participating in library protests and sit-ins during the 1960s.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2023 the Public Library Association of ALA published the *Public Library Services for Strong Communities Report* addressing the myriad ways libraries nationwide serve and sustain their communities.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] That same year, the Montana State Library Commission withdrew from the ALA, citing comments made by Emily Drabinski, who self-identified as a "Marxist lesbian".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The *Digital Public Library Ecosystem* was published by ALA in 2023.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] It is a comprehensive overview of the current state and operations of the relationships and roles of stakeholders including authors, agents, publishers, distributors, the library community, governments, and trade organizations.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2024, in response to proposed Georgia legislation that would prohibit public expenditures on the ALA, the ALA responded that the legislation "is based on false narratives", and the ALA "does not promote any 'ideology'".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Also in 2024, Association received the Toni Morrison Achievement Award from the National Book Critics Circle.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Also in 2024, the Library History Round Table published the "Bibliography of Library History" database containing over 7,000 entries for books, articles, and theses in library history and related fields published from 1990 to 2022.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2026 the 150th anniversary of the association was celebrated.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA Archives, including historical documents, non-current records, and digital records, are held at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign archives.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The establishment of the archives and the roles of David Horace Clift, Robert Wedgeworth, Beta Phi Mu, and the Library History Round Table has been documented by the first archivist, Maynard Britchford.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Additionally, the American Library Association Institutional Repository (ALAIR) provides digital access to the publications and intellectual work of the Association.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] ALA membership is open to any person or organization, though most of its members are libraries or librarians.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Most members live and work in the United States, with international members comprising 3.5% of total membership.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA is governed by an elected council and an executive board.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Policies and programs are administered by committees and round tables.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] One of the organization's most visible tasks is overseen by the Office for Accreditation, which formally reviews and authorizes American and Canadian academic institutions that offer degree programs in library and information science.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] ALA's president for the 2025-2026 term is Sam Helmick.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Secretaries of the Association prior to Carl Milam were George Burwell Utley (1911–20); Chalmers Hadley (1909–11); Edward C.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The official purpose of the association is "to promote library service and librarianship." Members may join one or more of eight membership divisions that deal with specialized topics such as academic, school, or public libraries, technical or reference services, and library administration.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Members may also join any of the nineteen round tables that are grouped around more specific interests and issues than the broader set of ALA divisions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Committee on Literacy develops and recommends the association's policies related to the promotion of multiple literacies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Chapter Relations Committee develops and recognizes chapters as integral components of ALA, encourages discussion, activities and programs that support the mutual interests of ALA and the chapters.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA is affiliated with regional, state, and student chapters across the country.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] It organizes conferences, participates in library standards development, and publishes books and periodicals.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA publishes the journals *American Libraries*, *Booklist* and *Choice*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Graphics Program creates and distributes products that promote libraries, literacy and reading.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Along with other organizations, it sponsors the annual Banned Books Week the last week of September.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Young Adult Library Services Association also sponsors Teen Read Week, the third week of each October, and Teen Tech Week, the second week of each March.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In addition, the ALA helps to promote diversity in the library profession with various outreach activities, including the Spectrum Scholarship program, which awards academic scholarships to minority library students each year.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA provides many scholarships (over $300,000 annually), a list of which can be found on their website.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] National Library Week, the second week of each April, is a national observance sponsored by the ALA since 1958.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Libraries across the country celebrate library resources, library champions and promote public outreach.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The American Library Association confers many professional recognition awards.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Association-wide awards include American Library Association Honorary Membership, the Joseph W.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Lippincott Award, the ALA Medal of Excellence and American Library Association Equality Award.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA annually confers numerous book and media awards, many through its children's and young adult divisions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Odyssey Award for best audiobook (joint with YALSA), and the (U.S.) Carnegie Medal and for best video.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] There are also two ALSC lifetime recognitions, the Children's Literature Legacy Award and the Arbuthnot Lecture.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Coretta Scott King Award honorees are awarded by the Coretta Scott King Book Awards Round Table.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The young-adult division, YALSA, administers the Margaret Edwards Award for significant and lasting contribution to YA literature, a lifetime recognition of one author annually, and annual awards that recognize particular works: the Michael L.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Printz Award for a YA book judged on literary merit alone, the William C.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Morris Award for an author's first YA book, the new "YALSA Award for Excellence in Nonfiction for Young Adults," and the "Alex Award" list of ten adult books having special appeal for teens.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Jointly with the children's division ALSC there is the Odyssey Award for excellence in audiobook production.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The award for YA nonfiction was inaugurated in 2012, defined by ages 12 to 18 and publication year November 2010 to October 2011.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The first winner was *The Notorious Benedict Arnold: A True Story of Adventure, Heroism & Treachery* by Steve Sheinkin (Roaring Brook Press, November 2010) and four other finalists were named.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Reference and User Services Association awards include annual lists of "Notable" and "Best" books and other media.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Reference and User Services Association awards also include the Andrew Carnegie Medals for Excellence in Fiction and Nonfiction, Dartmouth Medal, Sophie Brody Award and Schneider Book Awards.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Library History Round Table awards the Justin Winsor Prize for the best library history essay.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Rainbow RoundTable annually honors authors with the Stonewall Book Award.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The annual awards roster also includes the John Cotton Dana Award for excellence in library public relations, and the "I Love My Librarian" award in concert with the philanthropic foundation Carnegie Corporation of New York and the New York Public Library.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2000, the Office for Literacy and Outreach Services (OLOS) launched the Jean E.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Coleman Library Outreach Lecture in tribute to the work of the first OLOS director, Jean E.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Since 2006, the ALA has selected a class of Emerging Leaders, typically comprising about 100 librarians and library school students.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] This minor distinction is a form of organizational outreach to new librarians.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Emerging Leaders are allocated to project groups tasked with developing solutions to specified problems within ALA divisions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The class meets at the ALA Midwinter and Annual Meetings, commonly January and June.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Project teams may present posters of their completed projects at the Annual.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA and its divisions hold numerous conferences throughout the year.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The two largest conferences are the annual conference and the midwinter meeting, now called LibLearnX.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The latter is typically held in January and focuses on innovative session design concepts, while the annual conference is typically held in June and focuses on programs, exhibits, and presentations.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA annual conference is notable for being one of the largest professional conferences in existence, typically drawing over 25,000 attendees.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2020, Wanda Kay Brown was the first president in 75 years under whom the Annual Conference, scheduled for Chicago in June 2020, was cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA advocates positions on United States political issues that it believes are related to libraries and librarianship.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] For court cases that touch on issues about which the organization holds positions, the ALA often files amici curiae briefs, voluntarily offering information on some aspect of the case to assist the court in deciding a matter before it.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA has a Public Policy and Advocacy office in Washington, D.C., that lobbies Congress on issues relating to libraries, information and communication.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] It also provides materials to libraries that may include information on how to apply for grants, how to comply with the law, and how to oppose a law.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA maintains an Office for Intellectual Freedom (OIF), which is charged with "implementing ALA policies concerning the concept of intellectual freedom," defined as "the right of every individual to both seek and receive information from all points of view without restriction.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The first director, Judith Krug, headed the office for four decades, until her death in April 2009.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1950, the Intellectual Freedom Committee, the forerunner of the OIF, investigated the termination of Ruth W.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Brown as librarian of the Bartlesville Public Library, a position she held in the Oklahoma town for 30 years.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Brown's termination was based on the false allegation that she was a communist and that she had as part of the library's serials collection two left wing publications, *The New Republic* and *The Nation*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA support for her and the subsequent legal case was the first such investigation undertaken by the ALA or one of its state chapters.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 1999, radio personality Laura Schlessinger campaigned publicly against the ALA's intellectual freedom policy, specifically in regard to the ALA's refusal to remove a link on its web site to a specific sex-education site for teens.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The government appealed this decision, and on June 23, 2003, the Supreme Court of the United States upheld the law as constitutional as a condition imposed on institutions in exchange for government funding.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In upholding the law, the Supreme Court, adopting the interpretation urged by the U.S.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2021, the ALA released a statement signed by its executive board and Boards of Directors of its eight divisions in response to "a dramatic uptick in book challenges and outright removal of books from libraries".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] A spokesperson told ABC News that in her time working with reports of book challenges, she had "never seen such a widespread effort to remove books on racial and gender diversity".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) attempted to use librarians as possible informants in the conspiracy case of the Harrisburg Seven in 1971.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Harrisburg Seven, a group of religious anti-war activists, were primarily accused of conspiring to kidnap National Security Advisor Henry Kissinger.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The supposed leader of the group, Philip Berrigan, was serving time at the Lewisburg penitentiary.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The FBI sought "to use library surveillance and librarian informants" at Bucknell University as evidence of the Harrisburg Seven's "characters and intentions." Boyd Douglas became one such informant for the FBI: he was a prisoner at the same penitentiary with a work-release position at the library.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Boyd presented himself as an anti-war activist and offered to smuggle letters he collected while at work to Philip Berrigan at the prison.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The FBI also attempted to use Zoia Horn, a librarian at the Bucknell library, and interviewed other library workers.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The FBI met with Horn in her home to debrief her, but Horn refused to answer their questions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] She refused to testify, even after she was given immunity from self-incrimination.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Horn stated, "To me it stands on: Freedom of thought" and for the government to practice "spying in homes, in libraries and universities inhibits and destroys this freedom." Zoia Horn was charged with contempt of the court and served 20 days in jail.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] She was "the first librarian who spent time in jail for a value of our profession" according to Judith Krug of the American Library Association's Office for Intellectual Freedom.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Horn continued to fight for intellectual freedom in libraries and beyond.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Intellectual Freedom Committee of the California Library Association now awards the Zoia Horn Intellectual Freedom Award in honor of those who make contributions to intellectual freedom.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] As a result of these two situations and many others, the ALA affirmed the confidential status of all records which held patron names in a *Policy on the Confidentiality of Library Records*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA also released the ALA Statement on Professional Ethics in 1975 which advocated for the protection of the "confidential relationship" between a library user and a library.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA responded by writing to the FBI director.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] After several months of litigation, the lawsuit was dismissed when the FBI decided to withdraw the National Security Letter.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2007, the "Connecticut Four" were honored by the ALA with the Paul Howard Award for Courage for their challenge to the National Security Letter and gag order provision of the USA PATRIOT Act.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2006, the ALA sold humorous "radical militant librarian" buttons for librarians to wear in support of the ALA's stances on intellectual freedom, privacy, and civil liberties.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] Inspiration for the button's design came from documents obtained from the FBI by the Electronic Privacy Information Center (EPIC) through a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The request revealed a series of e-mails in which FBI agents complained about the "radical, militant librarians" while criticizing the reluctance of FBI management to use the secret warrants authorized under Section 215 of the USA PATRIOT Act.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] In 2018, the organization changed the name of the Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal to the Children's Literature Legacy Award.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] According to *The New York Times*, the name change was made "in order to distance the honor" from what the ALA described as "culturally insensitive portrayals" in Wilder's books.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] FCC,* successfully sued the Federal Communications Commission to prevent regulation that would enforce next-generation digital televisions to contain rights-management hardware.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] It has joined the Information Access Alliance to promote open access to research.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The Copyright Advisory Network of the association's Office for Information Technology Policy provides copyright resources to libraries and the communities they serve.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] The ALA is a member of the Library Copyright Alliance, along with the Association of Research Libraries and the Association of College and Research Libraries, which provides a unified voice for over 300,000 information professionals in the United States.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] ALA-accredited programs can be found at schools in the U.S., Puerto Rico, and Canada.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] These programs offer degrees with names such as Master of Library Science, Master of Arts, Master of Librarianship, Master of Library and Information Studies, and Master of Science.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/american-library-association] To be accredited, the program must undergo an external review and meet the Standards for Accreditation of Master's Programs in Library and Information Studies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The ***Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society*** is an academic journal on the history of science published annually by the Royal Society.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It publishes obituaries of Fellows of the Royal Society.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] It was established in 1932 as *Obituary Notices of Fellows of the Royal Society* and obtained its current title in 1955, with volume numbering restarting at 1.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Prior to 1932, obituaries were published in the *Proceedings of the Royal Society*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are a significant historical record and most include a full bibliography of works by the subjects.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] The memoirs are often written by a scientist of the next generation, often one of the subject's own former students, or a close colleague.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] In many cases the author is also a Fellow.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Notable biographies published in this journal include Albert Einstein, Alan Turing, Bertrand Russell, Claude Shannon, Clement Attlee, Ernst Mayr, and Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] Each year, around 40 to 50 memoirs of deceased Fellows of the Royal Society are collated by the Editor-in-Chief, currently Malcolm Longair, who succeeded Trevor Stuart in 2016.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-fellows-of-the-royal-society] All contents are freely available to read.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] The ***Biographical Memoirs of the National Academy of Sciences*** has been published by the United States National Academy of Sciences since 1877 and presents biographies of selected members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] This series of annual volumes, and the analogous British *Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society*, are "important examples of biographical serials".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] The entries in the series are written by an academy member familiar with the subject's work and are written after the subject's death.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Each entry includes a biography, a photo, and a copy of the subject's signature.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Recent biographies from this series have also been made available online.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] A **biography**, or simply **bio**, is a detailed description or account of a person's life.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] It involves more than just basic facts like education, work, relationships, and death; it portrays a person's experience of these life events.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Unlike a profile or curriculum vitae (résumé), a biography presents a subject's life story, highlighting various aspects of their life, including intimate details of experience, and may include an analysis of the subject's personality.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biographical works are usually non-fiction, but fiction can also be used to portray a person's life.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] One in-depth form of biographical coverage is called legacy writing.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Works in diverse media, from literature to film, form the genre known as biography.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] An **authorized biography** is written with the permission, cooperation, and at times, participation of a subject or a subject's heirs.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] An unauthorized biography is one written without such permission or participation.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] An autobiography is written by the person themselves, sometimes with the assistance of a collaborator or ghostwriter.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] At first, biographical writings were regarded merely as a subsection of history with a focus on a particular individual of historical importance.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The independent genre of biography as distinct from general history writing, began to emerge in the 18th century and reached its contemporary form at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biography is the earliest literary genre in history.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] According to Egyptologist Miriam Lichtheim, writing took its first steps toward literature in the context of the private tomb funerary inscriptions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] These were commemorative biographical texts recounting the careers of deceased high royal officials.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The earliest biographical texts are from the 26th century BC.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In the 21st century BC, another famous biography was composed in Mesopotamia about Gilgamesh.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] One of the five versions could be historical.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] From the same region a couple of centuries later, according to another famous biography, departed Abraham.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] He and his three descendants became subjects of ancient Hebrew biographies whether fictional or historical.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] 430 to 355/354 BC) wrote the biography of Cyrus, the founder of the Persian Empire.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] One of the earliest Roman biographers was Cornelius Nepos, who published his work *Excellentium Imperatorum Vitae* ("Lives of outstanding generals") in 44 BC.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Longer and more extensive biographies were written in Greek by Plutarch, in his *Parallel Lives*, published about 80 AD.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In this work famous Greeks are paired with famous Romans, for example, the orators Demosthenes and Cicero, or the generals Alexander the Great and Julius Caesar; some fifty biographies from the work survive.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Another well-known collection of ancient biographies is *De vita Caesarum* ("On the Lives of the Caesars") by Suetonius, written about 121 AD in the time of the emperor Hadrian.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Meanwhile, in the eastern imperial periphery, Gospel described the life of Jesus.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In the early Middle Ages (400–1450 AD), there was a decline in awareness of the classical culture in Europe.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] During this time, the only repositories of knowledge and records of the early history in Europe were those of the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Hermits, monks, and priests used this historic period to write biographies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Their subjects were usually restricted to the church fathers, martyrs, popes, and saints.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Their works were meant to be inspirational to the people and vehicles for conversion to Christianity (see Hagiography).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] One significant secular example of a biography from this period is the life of Charlemagne by his courtier Einhard.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In Medieval Western India, there was a Sanskrit Jain literary genre of writing semi-historical biographical narratives about the lives of famous persons called Prabandhas.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Prabandhas were written primarily by Jain scholars from the 13th century onwards and were written in colloquial Sanskrit (as opposed to Classical Sanskrit).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The earliest collection explicitly titled *Prabandha* is Jinabhadra's *Prabandhavali* (1234 CE).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] AD 750 to 1258), similar traditional Muslim biographies of Muhammad and other important figures in the early history of Islam began to be written, beginning the Prophetic biography tradition.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Early biographical dictionaries were published as compendia of famous Islamic personalities from the 9th century onwards.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] They contained more social data for a large segment of the population than other works of that period.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The earliest biographical dictionaries initially focused on the lives of the prophets of Islam and their companions, with one of these early examples being *The Book of The Major Classes* by Ibn Sa'd al-Baghdadi.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] And then began the documentation of the lives of many other historical figures (from rulers to scholars) who lived in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] By the late Middle Ages, biographies became less church-oriented in Europe as biographies of kings, knights, and tyrants began to appear.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The most famous of such biographies was *Le Morte d'Arthur* by Sir Thomas Malory.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The book was an account of the life of the fabled King Arthur and his Knights of the Round Table.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Following Malory, the new emphasis on humanism during the Renaissance promoted a focus on secular subjects, such as artists and poets, and encouraged writing in the vernacular.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Giorgio Vasari's *Lives of the Artists* (1550) was the landmark biography focusing on secular lives.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Vasari made celebrities of his subjects, as the *Lives* became an early "bestseller".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Two other developments are noteworthy: the development of the printing press in the 15th century and the gradual increase in literacy.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biographies in the English language began appearing during the reign of Henry VIII.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] John Foxe's *Actes and Monuments* (1563), better known as *Foxe's Book of Martyrs*, was essentially the first dictionary of the biography in Europe, followed by Thomas Fuller's *The History of the Worthies of England* (1662), with a distinct focus on public life.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Influential in shaping popular conceptions of pirates, *A General History of the Pyrates* (1724), by Charles Johnson, is the prime source for the biographies of many well-known pirates.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] A notable early collection of biographies of eminent men and women in the United Kingdom was *Biographia Britannica* (1747–1766) edited by William Oldys.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The American biography followed the English model, incorporating Thomas Carlyle's view that biography was a part of history.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Carlyle asserted that the lives of great human beings were essential to understanding society and its institutions.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] While the historical impulse would remain a strong element in early American biography, American writers carved out a distinct approach.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] What emerged was a rather didactic form of biography, which sought to shape the individual character of a reader in the process of defining national character.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The first modern biography, and a work that exerted considerable influence on the evolution of the genre, was James Boswell's *The Life of Samuel Johnson*, a biography of lexicographer and man-of-letters Samuel Johnson published in 1791.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] While Boswell's personal acquaintance with his subject only began in 1763, when Johnson was 54 years old, Boswell covered the entirety of Johnson's life by means of additional research.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Itself an important stage in the development of the modern genre of biography, it has been claimed to be the greatest biography written in the English language.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biographical writing generally stagnated during the 19th century – in many cases there was a reversal to the more familiar hagiographical method of eulogizing the dead, similar to the biographies of saints produced in Medieval times.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] A distinction between mass biography and literary biography began to form by the middle of the century, reflecting a breach between high culture and middle-class culture.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] However, the number of biographies in print experienced a rapid growth, thanks to an expanding reading public.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] This revolution in publishing made books available to a larger audience of readers.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In addition, affordable paperback editions of popular biographies were published for the first time.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Periodicals began publishing a sequence of biographical sketches.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Autobiographies became more popular, as with the rise of education and cheap printing, modern concepts of fame and celebrity began to develop.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The sciences of psychology and sociology were ascendant at the turn of the 20th century and would heavily influence the new century's biographies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The demise of the "great man" theory of history was indicative of the emerging mindset.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Human behavior would be explained through Darwinian theories.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] "Sociological" biographies conceived of their subjects' actions as the result of the environment, and tended to downplay individuality.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The development of psychoanalysis led to a more penetrating and comprehensive understanding of the biographical subject, and induced biographers to give more emphasis to childhood and adolescence.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Clearly these psychological ideas were changing the way biographies were written, as a culture of autobiography developed, in which the telling of one's own story became a form of therapy.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The conventional concept of heroes and narratives of success disappeared in the obsession with psychological explorations of personality.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] British critic Lytton Strachey revolutionized the art of biographical writing with his 1918 work *Eminent Victorians*, consisting of biographies of four leading figures from the Victorian era: Cardinal Manning, Florence Nightingale, Thomas Arnold, and General Gordon.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Strachey set out to breathe life into the Victorian era for future generations to read.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] His narrative demolished the myths that had built up around these cherished national heroes, whom he regarded as no better than a "set of mouth bungled hypocrites".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The book achieved worldwide fame due to its irreverent and witty style, its concise and factually accurate nature, and its artistic prose.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In the 1920s and 1930s, biographical writers sought to capitalize on Strachey's popularity by imitating his style.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] This new school featured iconoclasts, scientific analysts, and fictional biographers and included Gamaliel Bradford, André Maurois, and Emil Ludwig, among others.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Robert Graves (*I, Claudius*, 1934) stood out among those following Strachey's model of "debunking biographies." The trend in literary biography was accompanied in popular biography by a sort of "celebrity voyeurism", in the early decades of the century.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] This latter form's appeal to readers was based on curiosity more than morality or patriotism.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] By World War I, cheap hard-cover reprints had become popular.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] American professional historiography gives a limited role to biography, preferring instead to emphasize deeper social and cultural influences.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Political biographers historically incorporated moralizing judgments into their work, with scholarly biography being an uncommon genre before the mid-1920s.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Allan Nevins was a major contributor in the 1930s to the multi-volume *Dictionary of American Biography*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Nevins also sponsored a series of long political biographies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Later biographers sought to show how political figures balanced power and responsibility.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] However, many biographers found that their subjects were not as morally pure as they originally thought, and young historians after 1960 tended to be more critical.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The exception is Robert Remini whose books on Andrew Jackson idolize its hero and fends off criticisms.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The study of decision-making in politics is important for scholarly political biographers, who can take different approaches such as focusing on psychology/personality, bureaucracy/interests, fundamental ideas, or societal forces.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] However, most documentation favors the first approach, which emphasizes personalities.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biographers often neglect the voting blocs and legislative positions of politicians and the organizational structures of bureaucracies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] A more promising approach is to locate a person's ideas through intellectual history, but this has become more difficult with the philosophical shallowness of political figures in recent times.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Political biography can be frustrating and challenging to integrate with other fields of political history.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The feminist scholar Carolyn Heilbrun observed that women's biographies and autobiographies began to change character during the second wave of feminist activism.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In recent years, multimedia biography has become more popular than traditional literary forms.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Along with documentary biographical films, Hollywood produced numerous commercial films based on the lives of famous people.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The popularity of these forms of biography have led to the proliferation of TV channels dedicated to biography, including A&E, The Biography Channel, and The History Channel.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] CD-ROM and online biographies have also appeared.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Unlike books and films, they often do not tell a chronological narrative: instead they are archives of many discrete media elements related to an individual person, including video clips, photographs, and text articles.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biography-Portraits were created in 2001, by the German artist Ralph Ueltzhoeffer.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Media scholar Lev Manovich says that such archives exemplify the database form, allowing users to navigate the materials in many ways.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] General "life writing" techniques are a subject of scholarly study.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] In recent years, debates have arisen as to whether all biographies are fiction, especially when authors are writing about figures from the past.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] President of Wolfson College at Oxford University, Hermione Lee argues that all history is seen through a perspective that is the product of one's contemporary society and as a result, biographical truths are constantly shifting.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] So, the history biographers write about will not be the way that it happened; it will be the way they remembered it.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Debates have also arisen concerning the importance of space in life-writing.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biography Studies is emerging as an independent discipline, especially in the Netherlands.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] This Dutch School of biography is moving biography studies away from the less scholarly life writing tradition and towards history by encouraging its practitioners to utilize an approach adapted from microhistory.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] Biographical research is defined by Miller as a research method that collects and analyses a person's whole life, or portion of a life, through the in-depth and unstructured interview, or sometimes reinforced by semi-structured interview or personal documents.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] It is a way of viewing social life in procedural terms, rather than static terms.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The information can come from "oral history, personal narrative, biography and autobiography" or "diaries, letters, memoranda and other materials".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] The central aim of biographical research is to produce rich descriptions of persons or "conceptualise structural types of actions", which means to "understand the action logics or how persons and structures are interlinked".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] This method can be used to understand an individual's life within its social context or understand the cultural phenomena.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/biographies] There are many largely unacknowledged pitfalls to writing good biographies, and these largely concern the relation between firstly the individual and the context, and, secondly, the private and public.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] The **CRC Press** is a publishing imprint principally for technical books.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] Many of its books are related to engineering, science and mathematics.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] Its scope also includes books on business, forensics and information technology.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] In 2003 the imprint was acquired by Taylor & Francis, a subsidiary of Informa.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] The CRC Press and Routledge imprints are key components of Taylor & Francis's academic publishing.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] As of 2025, the branding of CRC Press presents it as part of the Routledge branding.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] The CRC Press originated as the publishing component of the **Chemical Rubber Company** (**CRC**) in 1903 by brothers Arthur, Leo and Emanuel Friedman in Cleveland, Ohio, based on an earlier enterprise by Arthur, who had begun selling rubber laboratory aprons in 1900.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] The company gradually expanded to include sales of laboratory equipment to chemists.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] In 1913 the CRC offered a short (116-page) manual called the *Rubber Handbook* as an incentive for any purchase of a dozen aprons.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] Since then the *Rubber Handbook* has evolved into the CRC's flagship book, the *CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics*.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] Another one of CRC's highly successful reference handbooks, *CRC Standard Mathematical Tables*, has sold over 2 million copies.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] In 1964, Chemical Rubber decided to focus on its publishing ventures, and in 1973 the company changed its name to CRC Press, Inc, and exited the manufacturing business, spinning off that line as the Lab Apparatus Company.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] In 1986, CRC Press was bought by the Times Mirror Company.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] Times Mirror began exploring the possibility of a sale of CRC Press in 1996, and in December announced the sale of CRC to Information Ventures.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/crc-press] In 2003, CRC became part of Taylor & Francis, which in 2004 became part of the UK publisher Informa.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] It was initially published in 1972 (ISO 4:1972), with a second edition published in 1984 (ISO 4:1984), and the third edition in 1997 (ISO 4:1997).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has appointed the ISSN International Centre as the registration authority for ISO 4.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] It maintains the **List of Title Word Abbreviations** (LTWA), which contains standard abbreviations for words commonly found in serial titles.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] The most recent LTWA was updated on 26 February 2024.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] As of April 2026, it includes over 37,000 abbreviations across more than 60 languages.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] One provision of ISO 4 is that components of compound words should be abbreviated.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] For hyphenated terms, each part is treated as a standalone word; for example, *African-American* becomes *Afr.Am.*, typically with periods and no spaces between components.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] A major use of ISO 4 is to abbreviate the names of scientific journals using the LTWA.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] For instance, under ISO 4 standards, the *Journal of Biological Chemistry* is cited as *J.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] Chem.*, and the *Journal of Polymer Science Part A* should be cited as *J.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] A* (capitalization is not specified by the standard).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] The standard notes that "Full stops shall only be used to indicate an abbreviation.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/iso-4-infobox] Full stops may be omitted from abbreviated words in applications that require limited use of punctuation" (section 4.6).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] As of May 2018 there were 2,382 active members and 484 international members, of whom approximately 190 have received Nobel Prizes.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] A full list of members can be found in the online members directory.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] See the list of members of the National Academy of Sciences and Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences for examples.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Critics have pointed to a lack of member diversity because of a selection bias for “old white men” who dominate membership of the Academy.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Elite institutions such as the from Ivy League, MIT, Stanford, the University of California and Caltech also dominate membership, thereby perpetuating the Matthew effect.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Diversity of age, disability, race, religion, gender and sexual orientation is lower in NAS than in the general population.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] For example, women in science are an underrepresented group in the Academy but the proportion of female members is slowly growing.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Persons of color are also underrepresented.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] New members and international members have been elected annually since 1863.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Membership can not be applied for as only voting academicians can submit formal nominations for newly elected members, for preferential voting in an annual ballot of members every March.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Candidates for membership are considered by peer review and voted for again through several rounds of balloting and a final annual ballot in April at the annual general meeting (AGM) of the academy with results announced shortly after, usually early May.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Each nomination includes a curriculum vitae (CV) with a 250 word summary of the nominee's scientific achievements, the basis for election and a list of no more than 12 of their most important papers published in scientific journals.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] The publication limit of 12 aims to focus assessment on the quality of a nominee's work, rather than the quantity of publications.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] As of 2026, a maximum of 120 members may be elected annually.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Non-citizens of the USA are elected as international members, with a maximum of 30 elected annually.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Newly elected members and international members are introduced at a presentation ceremony during the academy's annual meeting and sign the Registry of Membership.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Both members and international members are affiliated with a section in one of six scientific classes.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Since 1966, newly elected members of the National Academy of Sciences have been invited to contribute an inaugural year article (IYA) to *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America* (PNAS) which is accompanied by a brief biography of the author.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/member-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences] Biographies of deceased members are published in the *Biographical Memoirs of the National Academy of Sciences* (BMNAS), for example see David Arnett's biography of Alastair G.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The **National Academy of Sciences** (**NAS**) is an American nonprofit, non-governmental organization.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] NAS is part of the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, along with the National Academy of Engineering (NAE) and the National Academy of Medicine (NAM).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] As a national academy, new members of the organization are elected annually by current members, based on their distinguished and continuing achievements in original research.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Election to the National Academy is one of the highest honors in the scientific field in the United States.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Members of the National Academy of Sciences serve *pro bono* as "advisers to the nation" on science, engineering, and medicine.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The group holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The goal was somewhat unusual at the time, and also different from other knowledge-based entities serving a branch of government, such as the Library of Congress.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The academy receives no compensation from the government for its services.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] As of 2024, the National Academy of Sciences includes 2,687 NAS members and 531 international members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Some 190 members have won a Nobel Prize.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] By its own admission in 1989, the addition of women to the academy "continues at a dismal trickle"; at that time there were 1,516 male members and 57 female members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academy of Sciences is one of the 135 member organizations of the International Science Council (ISC).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Although there is no formal relationship with state and local academies of science, there often is informal dialogue.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academy is governed by a 17-member Council, made up of five officers (president, vice president, home secretary, international secretary, and treasurer) and 12 Councilors, all of whom are elected from among the academy membership.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Agencies of the United States government fund about 85 percent of the academy's activities.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Further funding comes from state governments, private foundations, and industrial organizations.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The council has the ability, ad hoc, to delegate certain tasks to committees.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] For example, the Committee on Animal Nutrition has produced a series of *Nutrient requirements of domestic animals* reports since at least 1944, each one being initiated by a different subcommittee of experts in the field, for example, on dairy cattle.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academy of Sciences meets annually in Washington, D.C., which is documented in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* (PNAS), its scholarly journal.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academies Press is the publisher for the National Academies and makes more than 5,000 publications freely available on its website.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] From 2004 to 2017, the National Academy of Sciences administered the Marian Koshland Science Museum to provide public exhibits and programming related to its policy work.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The museum's exhibits focused on climate change and infectious disease.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] In 2017, the museum closed and made way for a new science outreach program called LabX.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The Act of Incorporation, signed by President Abraham Lincoln on March 3, 1863, created the National Academy of Sciences and named 50 charter members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Many of the original NAS members came from the so-called "Scientific Lazzaroni", an informal network of mostly physical scientists working in the vicinity of Cambridge, Massachusetts (c.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] In 1863, the organizers enlisted the support of Alexander Dallas Bache and Charles Henry Davis, the latter a professional astronomer who had been recently recalled from the Navy to Washington, D.C. to head the Bureau of Navigation.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] They also elicited support from Swiss-American geologist Louis Agassiz and American mathematician Benjamin Peirce, who together planned the steps whereby the National Academy of Sciences was to be established.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Senator Henry Wilson of Massachusetts was to name Agassiz to the Board of Regents of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Agassiz was to come to Washington, D.C., at the government's expense to plan the organization with the others.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] This bypassed Joseph Henry, who was reluctant to have a bill for such an academy presented to Congress.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] He believed that such a resolution would be "opposed as something at variance with our democratic institutions".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Nevertheless, Henry later became the second President of NAS.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Agassiz, Davis, Peirce, Benjamin Gould, and Senator Wilson met at Bache's house and "hurriedly wrote the bill incorporating the Academy, including in it the name of fifty incorporators".
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] During the last hours of the session, when the Senate was immersed in the rush of last-minute business before its adjournment, Senator Wilson introduced the bill.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Without examining it or debating its provisions, both the Senate and House approved it, and President Lincoln signed it.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Although hailed as a great step forward in government recognition of the role of science in American society, at the time, the National Academy of Sciences created enormous ill feelings among scientists, whether or not they were named as incorporators.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academies did not solve the problems facing a nation in Civil War as the Lazzaroni had hoped, nor did it centralize American scientific efforts.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] However, election to the National Academy did come to be considered "the pinnacle of scientific achievement for Americans" until the establishment of the Nobel Prize at the end of the 19th century.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] In 1870, the congressional charter was amended to remove the limitation on the number of members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The academy currently (as of 2026) has 2,705 active members, with 557 international, non-voting members.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Existing members elect new members for life.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Up to 120 members are elected annually, while up to 30 foreign citizens may be elected as international members annually.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The election process begins with a formal nomination, followed by a vetting period, and culminates in a final ballot at the academy's annual meeting in April each year.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Over the entire history of the NAS, Harvard University is associated with the most members (331) overall, while the University of California at Berkeley is associated with the most members (255) without including the medical school.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Examples of top schools, UC Berkeley/MIT/Princeton/Caltech do not have medical schools, while Harvard/Stanford do.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The top ten institutions, two of which are from the University of California System and another four of which are in the Ivy League, account for nearly 28% of all members ever elected.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Those ten are also precisely the only institutions in the entire history of the NAS to have had 100 or more members overall.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] On the list for living members, only 14 institutions have 50 or more members overall, including the medical school (where it applies).
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] They represent 32% of all living members of the NAS.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academy of Sciences maintains multiple buildings around the United States.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The National Academy of Sciences Building is located at 2101 Constitution Avenue, in northwest Washington, D.C.; it sits on the National Mall, adjacent to the Marriner S.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Eccles Federal Reserve Board Building and in front of the headquarters of the U.S.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The building has a neoclassical architectural style and was built by architect Bertram Grosvenor Goodhue.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The building was dedicated in 1924 and is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Goodhue engaged a team of artists and architectural sculptors, including Albert Herter, Lee Lawrie, and Hildreth Meière to design interior embellishments celebrating the history and significance of science.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The building is used for lectures, symposia, exhibitions, and concerts, in addition to annual meetings of the NAS, NAE, and NAM.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Cultural Programs of the National Academy of Sciences hosts exhibitions exploring intersections of art, science, and culture such as Mathemalchemy.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The 2012 Presidential Award for Math and Science Teaching ceremony was held here on March 5, 2014.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Approximately 150 staff members work at the NAS Building.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] In June 2012, it reopened to visitors after a major two-year restoration project, which restored and improved the building's historic spaces, increased accessibility, and brought the building's aging infrastructure and facilities up to date.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] More than 1,000 National Academies staff members work at The Keck Center of the National Academies at 500 Fifth Street in northwest Washington, D.C.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The Keck Center provides meeting space and houses the National Academies Press Bookstore.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The Marian Koshland Science Museum of the National Academy of Sciences – formerly located at 525 E St., N.W. – hosted visits from the public, school field trips, and permanent science exhibits.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] NAS also maintains conference centers in California and Massachusetts.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The Arnold and Mabel Beckman Center is located on 100 Academy Drive in Irvine, California, near the campus of the University of California, Irvine; it offers a conference center and houses several NAS programs.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Erik Jonsson Conference Center, located at 314 Quissett Avenue in Woods Hole, Massachusetts, is an NAS conference facility.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The president is the head of the academy, elected by a majority vote of the membership to serve in this position for a term to be determined by the governing Council, not to exceed six years, and may be re-elected for a second term.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Terms usually start on July 1 and end on June 30.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The academy has had 22 presidents since its foundation.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The current president is geophysicist Marcia K.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] McNutt, the first woman to hold this position.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] In 2005, the national science academies of the G8 forum (including the National Academy of Sciences) and science academies of Brazil, China, and India (three of the largest emitters of greenhouse gases in the developing world) signed a statement on the global response to climate change.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] The statement stresses that the scientific understanding of climate change has become sufficiently clear to justify nations taking prompt action.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] On May 7, 2010, a letter signed by 255 Academy members was published in *Science* magazine, decrying "political assaults" against climate change scientists.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] This was in response to a civil investigative demand on the University of Virginia (UVA) by Virginia Attorney General Ken Cuccinelli, seeking a broad range of documents from Michael E.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Mann, a former UVA professor from 1999 to 2005.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Mann, who currently works at the University of Pennsylvania, is a climate change researcher, and Cuccinelli alleges that Mann may have defrauded Virginia taxpayers in the course of his environmental research.
[src:biographical-memoirs-of-the-national-academy-of-sciences/national-academy-of-sciences] Investigations had cleared Mann of charges that he falsified or suppressed data.
